<% let bigfont=font[0].id.split('-')[0]; const regex=/([a-z])([A-Z])/g; bigfont=bigfont.replace(regex, '$1 $2' ); %>
  <a href="../../typefaces/library/"><button class="back-button">Back</button></a>
  <button class="typeface-info"><%- bigfont %></button>

  <div class="specimenwrapper" style="font-family:<%- font[0].id %>">
    <div class="slidercontainer">
      <label for="font-style-selector">Styles: </label>
      <select id="font-style-selector">
        <% for (let i=0; i < selector.length; i++) { %>
          <% let styleName=selector[i].split("-")[1] || "Regular" ; %>
            <option value="<%= selector[i] %>">
              <%= styleName %>
            </option>
            <% } %>
      </select>
      <label for="fontSize">Fontsize</label>
      <input type="range" min="1" max="20" value="10" class="slider" id="fontSize">

      <label for="spacing">Spacing</label>
      <input type="range" min="-15" max="15" value="0" class="slider" id="spacing">

      <label for="spacing">Line Height</label>
      <input type="range" min="50" max="200" value="100" class="slider" id="line-height">
      <div class="reset" id="reset">Reset ↺</div>
    </div>

    <div class="bigfontcolumn" style="font-family:<%- font.id %>" id="font1" contenteditable="true">
      Burg Giebichenstein in Halle celebrates art, design, and jazz.
    </div>
    </br>

    <div class="hr-specimen"></div>
    <div class="abouttext">


        <div class="info"><span class="specimen-headline"><%- bigfont %> by <%- font[0].author %></span></div>
        <p class="p-about-text"><%- font[0].fontinfo %></p>
        <% if (font[0].teacher) { %>
          <p class="p-about-text">This Font was designed with supervision by <%- font[0].teacher %></p>
          <% } %>
            <p class="p-about-text">Categories: <%- font[0].category %></p>
            <a target="_blank" class="social-link" href="<%- font[0].instagram %>">Instagram</a>
            <a target="_blank" class="social-link" href="<%- font[0].website %>">Website</a>
    </div>

    <div class="charset" style=font-family:<%-font[0].id %>">
      <div class="specimen-headline" style="font-size:1.5rem; font-family: Graebenbach-Regular">Characterset</div>
      <div class="chars">ABCDEFGHIJKMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ
        abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz
        0123456789
        .,:;…!¡?¿·•*/\-–—_‚„“”‘’«»‹›"'(){}[]</div>


    </div>
    <div class="hr-specimen"></div>

    <div class="twocolumns size3">
      <div class="typesize">136 pt</div>
      <div>Stuck at Burg Halle's type class? Revamp with unique fonts, bring some flair.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="hr-specimen"></div>
    <div class="twocolumns size2">
      <div class="typesize">61pt</div>
      Typography transforms letters into an exquisite art form.
    </div>
    <div class="hr-specimen"></div>
    <div class="size1">
      <div class="typesize">40.5pt</div>
      As we revisit the world of typography at the Burg, do our perspectives shift and capture the picturesque beauty of
      typefaces?
    </div>
    <div class="size1 size1-right">
      <div class="typesize">27pt</div>
      On our return to Halle, will we soar over picturesque Unterburg?
      Queries of great enthusiasm transform into trivial waxy jokes.
      Nearly sixty artworks will craft a quarter pound of vibrant exhibitions at the University of Arts and Design.
      A misty haze engulfed the design school as jarring vibrations shattered windows in the building.
    </div>
    <div class="hr-specimen"></div>
    <div class="small-size">
      <div class="typesize">18pt</div>
      <div class="two-columns">Typographers are like scientists, but instead of beakers and Bunsen burners, they have a
        bunch of letters and a strong desire to make them look pretty. Or, at least, that's what they'd like you to
        believe. In reality, typography is just a bunch of people messing around with letters and pretending they know
        what they're doing. But hey, it looks good on the page, so who are we to argue?
      </div>

    </div>
    <div class="min-size">
      <div class="typesize">12pt</div>
      <div class="two-columns">Have you ever stopped to consider the sheer genius behind the way our letters are
        arranged on a page? No, us neither. But, as it turns out, there is an entire field dedicated to the study of
        such things – it's called typography. Typographers are like scientists, but instead of beakers and Bunsen
        burners, they have a bunch of letters and a strong desire to make them look pretty. They use the laws of
        physics, the mysteries of psychology, and a dash of pure magic to arrange letters in just the right way to
        create a visual feast for the reader's eyes. Or, at least, that's what they'd like you to believe. In reality,
        typography is just a bunch of people messing around with letters and pretending they know what they're doing.
        But hey, it looks good on the page, so who are we to argue? So, next time you're reading a book or scrolling
        through your favorite website, spare a thought for the typographers who put in the hard work to make sure your
        reading experience is as aesthetically pleasing as possible. Or don't. It's your call."</div>
    </div>
